WEBVTT

00:02.002 --> 00:04.545
(Wil Willis voice-over)
Since the dawn
of human civilization,

00:04.588 --> 00:06.380
mankind has made weapons.

00:06.424 --> 00:08.298
[fire whooshes]
- Whoa!

00:08.342 --> 00:11.510
(Wil)
Bladesmiths have honed
and perfected their craft

00:11.554 --> 00:13.012
over thousands of years.

00:13.055 --> 00:14.972
And now,
for the first time ever,

00:15.016 --> 00:16.765
these men will go head-to-head

00:16.809 --> 00:18.642
and put their skills
to the ultimate test.

00:18.686 --> 00:20.310
Welcome to the forge.

00:20.354 --> 00:23.313
(Wil voice-over)
It starts with a lump
of raw steel

00:23.357 --> 00:24.648
and a ticking clock,

00:24.692 --> 00:26.358
and by the end of three rounds,

00:26.402 --> 00:29.028
the bladesmiths must deliver
handmade weapons

00:29.071 --> 00:30.362
that are works of art

00:30.406 --> 00:33.282
as well as deadly instruments
of war.

00:33.325 --> 00:36.493
These weapons must survive
explosive tests

00:36.537 --> 00:39.913
as well as the scrutiny
of an expert panel of judges.

00:39.957 --> 00:44.001
In the end, only one bladesmith
will take home $10,000

00:44.045 --> 00:46.962
and be crowned
a<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

00:47.006 --> 00:49.965
[dramatic music]

00:50.009 --> 00:52.551
♪ ♪

00:53.721 --> 00:57.222
♪ ♪

00:57.266 --> 00:58.932
My name is JD Smith,

00:58.976 --> 01:02.019
and I'm a professor
at Massachusetts College of Art,

01:02.063 --> 01:03.479
where I teach bladesmithing.

01:03.522 --> 01:04.521
♪ ♪

01:04.565 --> 01:05.898
My name is Cowboy Szymanski.

01:05.941 --> 01:07.775
I'm a classically trained
bladesmith.

01:07.818 --> 01:09.735
I studied traditionally
as an apprentice,

01:09.779 --> 01:11.278
worked for living history
museums.

01:11.322 --> 01:12.863
I'm Guy Harris.

01:12.907 --> 01:14.531
I was an art major in school,

01:14.575 --> 01:15.908
and bladesmithing
has a lot of that in it.

01:15.951 --> 01:17.659
You're sculpting
a piece of steel

01:17.703 --> 01:19.036
into something meaningful.

01:19.080 --> 01:20.704
My name is Peter Martin.

01:20.748 --> 01:21.955
I was a hunter.

01:21.999 --> 01:23.248
Back in the '80s,

01:23.292 --> 01:24.708
the factory knives
were not the best,

01:24.752 --> 01:26.376
and I decided
to take on knife making

01:26.420 --> 01:27.669
as a full-time career.

01:27.713 --> 01:30.255
Gentlemen,
welcome to the forge.

01:30.299 --> 01:32.633
Ahead of you are three
challenges

01:32.676 --> 01:35.052
designed to test
your craftsmanship

01:35.096 --> 01:37.554
in a highly pressurized arena.

01:37.598 --> 01:40.182
Each round is against
the clock and each other.

01:40.226 --> 01:41.892
At the end of each round,

01:41.936 --> 01:44.728
you will hand your work over
to our panel of expert judges,

01:44.772 --> 01:47.272
and they will decide who
ultimately has the opportunity

01:47.316 --> 01:49.358
to compete for $10,000

01:49.401 --> 01:53.070
and the title
of<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

01:53.114 --> 01:55.030
It's time to meet our judges.

01:55.074 --> 02:00.077
First up, internationally known
master bladesmith, J. Neilson,

02:00.121 --> 02:03.664
Rare weapons recreation
specialist, David Baker,

02:03.707 --> 02:05.791
and finally,
edged weapon specialist

02:05.835 --> 02:07.835
and martial artist,
Doug Marcaida.

02:07.878 --> 02:09.628
It's time to get to work.

02:09.672 --> 02:12.422
In front of you
on your anvils is a cloth.

02:12.466 --> 02:14.341
Go ahead and lift that up.

02:14.385 --> 02:18.011
♪ ♪

02:18.055 --> 02:20.180
That is an empty canister.

02:20.224 --> 02:23.600
Your challenge is
to fill that canister

02:23.644 --> 02:24.768
with the materials
and metals

02:24.812 --> 02:26.478
here on the tables
in front of you.

02:26.522 --> 02:29.481
You must use at least
two of the metals

02:29.525 --> 02:31.608
in addition
to the powdered steel

02:31.652 --> 02:34.319
and forge that together
within your canister.

02:34.363 --> 02:37.447
It is your option to either peel
or grind the canister away

02:37.491 --> 02:40.325
to reveal
the Damascus steel within.

02:40.369 --> 02:42.452
From that billet of Damascus,

02:42.496 --> 02:45.789
you must forge a blade
in your signature style.

02:45.833 --> 02:48.959
The length of the blade,
not including the tang,

02:49.003 --> 02:53.297
must be between
9 and 13 inches.

02:53.340 --> 02:54.882
And this week,
because the challenge is

02:54.925 --> 02:56.800
so technically demanding,

02:56.844 --> 02:59.761
you will have four hours
to forge your weapons.

02:59.805 --> 03:01.638
And to make it
a little more challenging,

03:01.682 --> 03:04.474
this week there will be
no design period.

03:04.518 --> 03:07.186
After our first round,
one of you will have to

03:07.229 --> 03:10.355
hand in his weapon
and leave the forge.

03:10.399 --> 03:12.357
Good luck, gentlemen.

03:12.401 --> 03:15.569
Your time starts now.

03:15.613 --> 03:18.530
♪ ♪

03:18.574 --> 03:21.575
As a bladesmith,
I'm a stylist

03:21.619 --> 03:25.329
but without a real
definable style, in my opinion.

03:25.372 --> 03:28.540
But the bowie knife is
an incredible weapon,

03:28.584 --> 03:30.042
and that's what I do best.

03:30.085 --> 03:31.668
Here we go.

03:31.712 --> 03:35.005
Making blades for me
is a process like no other.

03:35.049 --> 03:36.840
I feel almost godlike
doing it,

03:36.884 --> 03:40.260
taking something from nothing,
basically creating something

03:40.304 --> 03:42.721
of incredible
beauty and utility.

03:42.765 --> 03:45.390
(Cowboy)
My specialty is making
hunting knives.

03:45.434 --> 03:48.018
What I'm gonna make is a tanto.

03:48.062 --> 03:52.522
I like to make very simplistic,
useful pieces of art.

03:52.566 --> 03:56.526
I'm often inspired by history,
but I'm not obligated to it.

03:56.570 --> 03:58.487
My knife has a lot in common
with the bowie knife--

03:58.530 --> 04:00.614
just the basic profile.

04:00.658 --> 04:04.034
Most of my blades have
historical elements to them,

04:04.078 --> 04:08.247
but more often than not,
I focus on functionality.

04:08.290 --> 04:11.917
(Peter)
I am ecstatic about the
materials that they've put down:

04:11.961 --> 04:13.252
pieces of chain saw chain,

04:13.295 --> 04:15.796
the small ball bearings,
band saw blades.

04:15.839 --> 04:17.339
They all make good knives.

04:17.383 --> 04:19.007
The type of blade
that I'm making

04:19.051 --> 04:21.927
is gonna be just a camp knife,
just a general design.

04:21.971 --> 04:23.887
My style of knives
when I first started off in this

04:23.931 --> 04:25.764
was very large, straight knives.

04:25.808 --> 04:28.558
Nowadays, all my stuff
is Damascus--

04:28.602 --> 04:30.560
very sharp, very clean,
and very pretty.

04:30.604 --> 04:32.938
(Wil)
Where do you start
with this canister Damascus?

04:32.982 --> 04:34.231
Well, the first thing
you got to do is,

04:34.275 --> 04:36.650
you got to get
that bottom cap on,

04:36.694 --> 04:39.444
because once they have
the bottom cap on,

04:39.488 --> 04:41.571
they need that to start
filling their can up.

04:41.615 --> 04:45.409
(Wil)
So Peter's going for
some of that chain saw chain.

04:45.452 --> 04:47.244
When you're talking
about Damascus,

04:47.288 --> 04:49.579
there is a huge part of that
is very artistic.

04:49.623 --> 04:51.623
That pattern manipulation.

04:51.667 --> 04:53.583
But the actual fusion
of the two metals

04:53.627 --> 04:55.002
is very mechanical.

04:55.045 --> 04:57.421
The more material
you pack in there,

04:57.464 --> 04:58.880
the more pattern
you'll get at the end.

04:58.924 --> 05:00.924
♪ ♪

05:00.968 --> 05:02.592
(Cowboy)
This is a very unique challenge.

05:02.636 --> 05:04.261
It's a very difficult challenge.

05:04.305 --> 05:05.637
I know it's a very
common process,

05:05.681 --> 05:07.097
but it's not one
I've done before.

05:07.141 --> 05:09.766
Cowboy just put in
some chain saw chain

05:09.810 --> 05:11.268
along with some saw blade steel,

05:11.312 --> 05:13.270
and now he's
putting his powder in.

05:13.314 --> 05:15.355
(Wil)
And what's that powder
he's throwing in there?

05:15.399 --> 05:17.149
It's basically
steel talcum powder.

05:17.192 --> 05:18.817
♪ ♪

05:18.861 --> 05:21.820
I'm trying to set my canister
as tight as I can.

05:21.864 --> 05:23.613
Snug fit, pack it in tight.

05:23.657 --> 05:26.616
I've never done
canister Damascus.

05:26.660 --> 05:28.618
I've seen an Internet video,

05:28.662 --> 05:30.954
and that's about
my experience with it.

05:30.998 --> 05:33.498
Guy, he grabbed
some chain saw chains,

05:33.542 --> 05:34.666
ball bearings,

05:34.710 --> 05:36.293
a little of this,
a little of that,

05:36.337 --> 05:38.086
so we're gonna see
some cool stuff here.

05:38.130 --> 05:40.172
♪ ♪

05:40.215 --> 05:43.300
(JD)
I'm going for
what they call dragon skin

05:43.344 --> 05:44.843
with the ball bearings.

05:44.887 --> 05:46.553
When it's done properly,
it can, you know,

05:46.597 --> 05:48.221
it can be a very
beautiful pattern.

05:48.265 --> 05:49.306
(Doug)
We said you have to use

05:49.350 --> 05:51.141
at least two pieces.

05:51.185 --> 05:53.727
(J)
Two types of metal
aside from the powdered steel.

05:53.771 --> 05:55.270
Well, so far JD is
only putting in

05:55.314 --> 05:56.605
ball bearing
and powdered steel.

05:56.648 --> 05:58.398
♪ ♪

05:58.442 --> 06:02.819
If JD has only used the
powder and the ball bearings,

06:02.863 --> 06:04.321
will you be able to look
at that blade and tell that?

06:04.365 --> 06:06.031
(J)
Yes.

06:06.075 --> 06:07.532
(Wil)
That's gonna be
a problem in the judging.

06:07.576 --> 06:08.575
- Absolutely.
- Oh, yeah.

06:08.619 --> 06:10.869
♪ ♪

06:10.913 --> 06:12.662
(David)
Pete's got his canister
in the fire.

06:12.706 --> 06:13.663
(J)
Oh, wow.

06:13.707 --> 06:15.123
He's in the forge.

06:15.167 --> 06:17.626
Heating it up.
Get it hot.

06:17.669 --> 06:19.503
(David)
All right, Cowboy is
going in the fire.

06:19.546 --> 06:20.962
- Cowboy is in.
- Here we go.

06:21.006 --> 06:22.506
All right, two in the fire.

06:22.549 --> 06:23.840
♪ ♪

06:23.884 --> 06:25.175
(Wil)
Is there any way for these guys

06:25.219 --> 06:27.302
to be able
to absolutely determine

06:27.346 --> 06:31.014
that the center of that billet
that they're creating

06:31.058 --> 06:33.183
is at a temperature where
it's gonna weld effectively?

06:33.227 --> 06:34.434
For a can like this,

06:34.478 --> 06:36.186
when the outside
shell of the can,

06:36.230 --> 06:37.896
actually looks like
it's starting to turn liquid

06:37.940 --> 06:39.689
and about to start dripping off,

06:39.733 --> 06:41.149
that's the perfect time
to grab it and set your weld.

06:41.193 --> 06:42.776
(Wil)
Okay.

06:42.820 --> 06:46.363
After I filled up my canister
and I waited for it

06:46.407 --> 06:48.365
in the forge,
keep flipping it

06:48.409 --> 06:50.867
until I'm confident
that the interior temperature

06:50.911 --> 06:52.619
is that of the
exterior temperature.

06:52.663 --> 06:56.331
I walk over to the press;
I start squeezing it down,

06:56.375 --> 06:59.251
little bit by little bit,
constantly turning the bar

06:59.294 --> 07:01.878
until it's solid
or loses temperature.

07:01.922 --> 07:03.964
Then I'm back into the forge
for another round.

07:04.007 --> 07:06.091
♪ ♪

07:06.135 --> 07:08.385
(Wil)
Setting the weld
on the Damascus,

07:08.429 --> 07:10.595
is that a make-or-break moment
for these guys?

07:10.639 --> 07:11.972
(J)
Oh, absolutely.

07:12.015 --> 07:13.390
If you think you've
got it all done,

07:13.434 --> 07:14.850
you peel it apart,
and you go to grind it

07:14.893 --> 07:16.059
or cut into it,

07:16.103 --> 07:17.602
the whole center
could just collapse.

07:17.646 --> 07:19.354
♪ ♪

07:19.398 --> 07:22.232
You think JD doesn't realize
that that's not his forge?

07:22.276 --> 07:23.775
[laughter]

07:23.819 --> 07:25.235
(Wil)
Look at Cowboy right now.

07:25.279 --> 07:27.195
Cowboy is like,
"What the hell is going on?"

07:27.239 --> 07:32.075
♪ ♪

07:32.119 --> 07:33.577
Thank you for
holding my spot for me.

07:33.620 --> 07:34.578
Oh, [bleep].

07:34.621 --> 07:35.579
[laughter]

07:35.622 --> 07:36.580
Sorry.

07:36.623 --> 07:38.748
[laughs]

07:38.792 --> 07:43.086
Gentlemen, you have two hours
remaining to finish your work.

07:43.130 --> 07:45.630
(Wil)
So it looks like Cowboy,
Guy, and Peter

07:45.674 --> 07:49.217
are grinding their cans off
instead of peeling them off.

07:49.261 --> 07:51.303
Right now, we've got
dueling grinders, it looks like.

07:51.346 --> 07:52.971
(Doug)
How beautiful is that?

07:53.015 --> 07:54.389
It's like a water cannon
fight with fire.

07:54.433 --> 08:00.228
♪ ♪

08:00.272 --> 08:02.772
I'm starting to get worried
that Peter has a blade

08:02.816 --> 08:04.274
that's over 13 inches.

08:04.318 --> 08:05.775
(J)
Looks pretty big, yeah.

08:05.819 --> 08:07.652
You can't lose sight
of the parameters.

08:07.696 --> 08:09.154
I'm ready for grinding.

08:09.198 --> 08:11.114
I really don't want
to make a shorter blade,

08:11.158 --> 08:12.282
because I'm making

08:12.326 --> 08:14.284
a chopping and stabbing
instrument,

08:14.328 --> 08:16.077
so I'm thinking
about stretching it

08:16.121 --> 08:17.704
as far as I can get it.

08:17.748 --> 08:20.165
If that grinder works
half as good as I do,

08:20.209 --> 08:21.958
we'll earn the money.

08:22.002 --> 08:24.461
♪ ♪

08:24.505 --> 08:26.296
(J)
We got Guy working on his tip.

08:26.340 --> 08:27.547
I'm happy to see that.

08:27.591 --> 08:29.049
♪ ♪

08:29.092 --> 08:30.717
Everybody else
has got their steel.

08:30.761 --> 08:32.802
They're starting to forge it,
grinding it down.

08:32.846 --> 08:34.304
JD is the only one
that's still working

08:34.348 --> 08:35.639
on peeling his can away.

08:35.682 --> 08:36.848
♪ ♪

08:36.892 --> 08:39.100
The slice that I
was making in it,

08:39.144 --> 08:42.938
they weren't quite lining up,
and that made it very difficult

08:42.981 --> 08:45.190
for me to actually
chisel it off.

08:45.234 --> 08:46.483
♪ ♪

08:46.527 --> 08:48.652
This is gonna cost me some time,

08:48.695 --> 08:52.197
and the clock is definitely
a ticking time bomb.

08:52.241 --> 08:53.490
♪ ♪

08:53.534 --> 08:54.491
I'm really worried
about JD.

08:54.535 --> 08:55.492
[bleep].

08:55.536 --> 08:57.661
♪ ♪

09:01.959 --> 09:03.583
♪ ♪

09:03.627 --> 09:05.752
Everybody else
has got their steel.

09:05.796 --> 09:07.837
They're starting to forge it,
grinding it down.

09:07.881 --> 09:09.673
JD is the only one
that's still working

09:09.716 --> 09:11.049
on peeling his can away.

09:11.093 --> 09:12.759
The cooler it gets,
the harder it is to move.

09:12.803 --> 09:14.511
Right.

09:14.555 --> 09:15.929
It's easier to peel it apart
when you got some heat

09:15.973 --> 09:18.348
left in that canister steel.

09:18.392 --> 09:19.891
(J)
There we go;
separate it.

09:19.935 --> 09:21.518
It just popped loose.

09:21.562 --> 09:22.519
(Wil)
There we go;
it just popped loose.

09:22.563 --> 09:23.520
He's all good to go.

09:23.564 --> 09:25.105
Look at that.

09:25.148 --> 09:27.357
Now that inside of there
is a piece of Damascus.

09:27.401 --> 09:28.858
Yes, it is.

09:28.902 --> 09:31.236
I might be running
a bit behind right now,

09:31.280 --> 09:34.030
but I can make that time up
in the other processes

09:34.074 --> 09:35.532
that I'm really good at.

09:35.576 --> 09:36.741
♪ ♪

09:36.785 --> 09:38.076
(J)
It looks like JD is using

09:38.120 --> 09:39.661
a little bit
of the edge of the hammer,

09:39.705 --> 09:42.622
a little bit of a press
to actually force it down.

09:42.666 --> 09:44.416
(JD)
When I'm standing
behind that anvil

09:44.459 --> 09:46.001
with a hammer in my hand

09:46.044 --> 09:48.545
and a hot piece of steel
in the other hand,

09:48.589 --> 09:50.880
I'm good as some,
better than most,

09:50.924 --> 09:52.799
and I'm here to smoke
their bacon.

09:52.843 --> 09:57.095
♪ ♪

09:57.139 --> 10:00.390
Guy, it looks like has
just enough metal

10:00.434 --> 10:02.892
to make a knife
of the appropriate size,

10:02.936 --> 10:04.603
so I'm a little bit
worried about him.

10:04.646 --> 10:08.898
♪ ♪

10:08.942 --> 10:10.650
One thing that's
worrying me about Cowboy

10:10.694 --> 10:13.903
is that his blade was not
excessively thick to begin with,

10:13.947 --> 10:15.947
and he's been spending
a lot of time on that grinder.

10:15.991 --> 10:19.868
I'm gonna go with a short blade
because you have more chances

10:19.911 --> 10:24.581
of flaws happening in your piece
the larger the piece is.

10:24.625 --> 10:26.416
30 minutes, gentlemen.

10:26.460 --> 10:29.252
30 minutes is a lot of time
when I'm on the job.

10:29.296 --> 10:31.588
♪ ♪

10:31.632 --> 10:34.758
And Guy just quenched.

10:34.801 --> 10:37.594
Up to this point,
it's been all fun and games.

10:37.638 --> 10:40.263
The quench is where
everything happens.

10:40.307 --> 10:41.306
Either make it or break it.

10:41.350 --> 10:42.265
(Doug)
Here you go.

10:42.309 --> 10:43.600
Peter just quenched.

10:43.644 --> 10:44.934
(Wil)
Peter's in the oil.

10:44.978 --> 10:46.102
Whoo-hoo.

10:46.146 --> 10:47.062
(Peter)
When I pull it out,

10:47.105 --> 10:48.605
everything looks perfect.

10:48.649 --> 10:50.106
I didn't feel
any tinging in the tongs,

10:50.150 --> 10:51.775
'cause that'll tell you
if it cracked.

10:51.818 --> 10:53.860
I don't see any severe warping,

10:53.904 --> 10:55.987
so I'm very confident
about this.

10:56.031 --> 10:59.949
(Dave)
Has anybody seen him
check that against a ruler?

10:59.993 --> 11:02.077
- I have not.
- I haven't seen it once.

11:02.120 --> 11:08.333
♪ ♪

11:08.377 --> 11:11.169
(Cowboy)
The most stress that I have
is the quench.

11:11.213 --> 11:12.837
As I'm looking down,

11:12.881 --> 11:15.965
I've already seen
that the blade is warped on it.

11:16.009 --> 11:17.801
I might be screaming
on the inside,

11:17.844 --> 11:19.803
but I have realized
that if I panic,

11:19.846 --> 11:21.054
I'm gonna be in trouble.

11:21.098 --> 11:22.847
(Doug)
Yeah, he picked up a warp.

11:22.891 --> 11:24.474
(J)
Oh, yeah, you can
see it from here, actually.

11:24.518 --> 11:25.975
It's that thin blade.

11:26.019 --> 11:27.644
I'm gonna quench it again,

11:27.688 --> 11:29.396
and hopefully
it'll stay straight this time.

11:29.439 --> 11:34.526
♪ ♪

11:34.569 --> 11:36.027
It's warped again on me.

11:36.071 --> 11:39.698
It's a rough setback.

11:39.741 --> 11:41.199
We're just gonna go with it
and see what happens.

11:41.243 --> 11:42.867
♪ ♪

11:42.911 --> 11:44.119
Ten minutes!

11:44.162 --> 11:45.995
Time for a nap.

11:46.039 --> 11:47.414
(Wil)
All right, Peter,
what are you sitting down for?

11:47.457 --> 11:48.373
You got ten minutes left.

11:48.417 --> 11:50.041
Peter decided he's done.

11:50.085 --> 11:53.169
We've seen that come back
and bite a few people.

11:53.213 --> 11:54.295
That's the one right there.

11:54.339 --> 11:55.672
♪ ♪

11:55.716 --> 11:57.841
(J)
All right, JD is
off the grinder.

11:57.884 --> 11:59.008
- Oh.
- Yep, here we go.

11:59.052 --> 12:00.135
- Here we go.
- All right.

12:00.178 --> 12:01.136
Okay.

12:01.179 --> 12:02.679
♪ ♪

12:02.723 --> 12:03.680
(J)
And he's in the oil.

12:03.724 --> 12:04.848
There we go.

12:04.891 --> 12:06.266
(Dave)
We have got four blades

12:06.309 --> 12:08.101
that are in contention,

12:08.145 --> 12:10.353
as far as we know.

12:10.397 --> 12:12.522
(Wil)
Ten, nine,

12:12.566 --> 12:14.399
eight, seven,

12:14.443 --> 12:16.192
six, five,

12:16.236 --> 12:18.611
four, three,

12:18.655 --> 12:20.530
two, one.

12:20.574 --> 12:23.950
Gentlemen, your forge time
is now complete.

12:23.994 --> 12:29.956
♪ ♪

12:30.000 --> 12:31.541
I'm very confident
that I met all the requirements

12:31.585 --> 12:33.251
necessary to pull this
challenge off,

12:33.295 --> 12:35.378
so I'm feeling very, very good.

12:35.422 --> 12:37.881
(JD)
Normally, when I look
at my blades,

12:37.924 --> 12:41.301
I'm thinking,
"Yeah, that's a sexy blade."

12:41.344 --> 12:42.761
But this one,
phew.

12:42.804 --> 12:46.347
I hope this isn't
a beauty contest.

12:46.391 --> 12:48.767
(Wil)
Gentlemen, it looks
like all of you

12:48.810 --> 12:50.226
have produced something

12:50.270 --> 12:51.895
you'd be proud
to put your name on.

12:51.938 --> 12:53.521
Now we're gonna let the judges

12:53.565 --> 12:55.064
take a look at your work.

12:55.108 --> 12:57.650
Cowboy, please present
your blade to the judges.

12:57.694 --> 13:01.196
♪ ♪

13:01.239 --> 13:02.989
(J)
Cowboy, I like
the profile of this,

13:03.033 --> 13:04.574
especially for
a thrusting knife.

13:04.618 --> 13:06.910
You've got quite a wiggle
on the blade edge there.

13:06.953 --> 13:08.578
(Cowboy)
Yes, I did.

13:08.622 --> 13:10.663
(J)
That's gonna be
a bit of a concern.

13:10.707 --> 13:12.749
- Beautiful.
- Thank you.

13:12.793 --> 13:13.917
You've got the tanto
design there.

13:13.960 --> 13:15.919
That's well known for piercing.

13:15.962 --> 13:19.756
I see the curve there,
but that can be fixed.

13:19.800 --> 13:21.591
Guy, you're up next.

13:21.635 --> 13:23.259
Please present your weapon.

13:23.303 --> 13:26.262
♪ ♪

13:26.306 --> 13:28.640
Well, Guy, for never
doing a canister weld before,

13:28.683 --> 13:29.849
I'm pretty impressed.

13:29.893 --> 13:32.018
You got some nice
patterning here.

13:32.062 --> 13:35.271
I notice you got a couple
small chips in the blade here.

13:35.315 --> 13:37.148
I was a little worried
you were getting this blade

13:37.192 --> 13:39.317
really thin when you were
on that grinder.

13:39.361 --> 13:40.985
Yeah, if I was doing it again,

13:41.029 --> 13:42.487
I would leave a little
more material.

13:42.531 --> 13:45.281
But all in all,
it's a good shape.

13:45.325 --> 13:46.783
- Good work.
- Thank you.

13:46.827 --> 13:48.535
JD,

13:48.578 --> 13:51.371
please present your weapon
to the judges.

13:51.414 --> 13:53.957
♪ ♪

13:54.000 --> 13:56.793
(J)
Well, JD, I got to say,
I love the overall profile.

13:56.837 --> 13:58.837
Nice traditional
thrusting spearpoint.

13:58.880 --> 14:01.130
My big concern is, though,
when we were watching you

14:01.174 --> 14:03.132
build your can
for this challenge,

14:03.176 --> 14:04.843
we required two steels

14:04.886 --> 14:06.886
aside from the powder
in that canister.

14:06.930 --> 14:08.805
How many did you put
in this blade?

14:08.849 --> 14:10.306
Just two.

14:10.350 --> 14:12.183
So it was just the powder
and ball bearings?

14:13.979 --> 14:16.396
I wasn't paying attention,

14:16.439 --> 14:18.314
and it slipped my mind.

14:18.358 --> 14:21.401
Not something I realized
until the end, actually.

14:21.444 --> 14:22.652
Okay.

14:22.696 --> 14:24.195
♪ ♪

14:24.239 --> 14:26.573
Okay, Peter, present
your weapon to the judges.

14:26.616 --> 14:29.325
♪ ♪

14:29.369 --> 14:33.413
I'm starting to feel sorry
for the target for the test.

14:33.456 --> 14:35.999
How long is this?

14:36.042 --> 14:37.917
Uh, 12 and some change
for the blade.

14:37.961 --> 14:40.461
It looks really big to me.

14:40.505 --> 14:43.715
♪ ♪

14:43.758 --> 14:46.885
Yeah, I'm getting 13 1/2.

14:46.928 --> 14:47.886
You're over.

14:47.929 --> 14:50.054
Didn't pay attention.

14:50.098 --> 14:51.890
We know that in
the heat of competition,

14:51.933 --> 14:54.058
things will slip by,
but you had so much time

14:54.102 --> 14:56.394
to go back
and get the meat off that.

14:56.438 --> 14:59.981
But still, I mean,
that's a nice blade right there.

15:00.025 --> 15:01.858
♪ ♪

15:01.902 --> 15:05.028
(Wil)
So, gentlemen, given the fact
that two of you

15:05.071 --> 15:08.615
didn't meet the required
specifications,

15:08.658 --> 15:10.241
the judges will now
take some time

15:10.285 --> 15:11.534
to decide what to do.

15:11.578 --> 15:13.119
Thank you.

15:13.163 --> 15:20.752
♪ ♪

15:20.795 --> 15:22.712
(Wil)
Okay, we had two blades

15:22.756 --> 15:25.256
that didn't meet
the parameters of the challenge.

15:25.300 --> 15:28.217
Looks like you judges
have a pretty tough decision.

15:28.261 --> 15:30.762
Let's talk about Peter's blade.

15:30.805 --> 15:33.222
How far over the maximum
of 13 inches is he?

15:33.266 --> 15:35.558
(Dave)
3/4 inch, as far as I can tell.

15:35.602 --> 15:38.394
Yeah, just a little over 3/4.

15:38.438 --> 15:41.230
That's amazing how
these little details can,

15:41.274 --> 15:45.068
like, get past you when
you're in the heat of battle.

15:45.111 --> 15:46.819
(Wil)
Let's talk about JD's blade.

15:46.863 --> 15:48.738
I can't get over the fact
that it doesn't have

15:48.782 --> 15:51.908
enough of the steels
in the Damascus itself.

15:51.952 --> 15:53.451
(Doug)
Can we measure
the length on that?

15:53.495 --> 15:56.913
- So it's just under 9.
- Just under 9.

15:56.957 --> 16:01.167
(Wil)
So that blade is clearly
under the 9-inch minimum.

16:01.211 --> 16:03.127
Have you guys made a decision?

16:03.171 --> 16:04.420
(J)
Yes.

16:04.464 --> 16:06.422
- Yeah.
- Yep.

16:06.466 --> 16:08.091
All right, well, let's go
tell our contestants.

16:08.134 --> 16:14.430
♪ ♪

16:14.474 --> 16:17.725
Gentlemen, two of you
turned in blades

16:17.769 --> 16:20.103
that had critical failures
in them.

16:20.146 --> 16:23.231
One of you must now
leave the forge.

16:23.274 --> 16:26.442
♪ ♪

16:26.486 --> 16:29.529
JD, you did not make the cut.

16:29.572 --> 16:30.947
♪ ♪

16:30.991 --> 16:33.825
JD, it was truly a pleasure
watching you work,

16:33.868 --> 16:35.284
but on the blade
you presented us,

16:35.328 --> 16:37.120
you didn't have enough
of the required steels

16:37.163 --> 16:39.872
in your Damascus billet,
and when we measured it,

16:39.916 --> 16:41.290
it came out
just a little bit short

16:41.334 --> 16:43.459
of the parameters we laid out.

16:43.503 --> 16:45.003
And for these reasons,
we had no choice

16:45.046 --> 16:46.087
but to cut you loose.

16:46.131 --> 16:47.964
♪ ♪

16:48.008 --> 16:51.300
JD, please surrender
your blade.

16:51.344 --> 16:53.302
♪ ♪

16:53.346 --> 16:54.971
Thank you, sir.

16:55.015 --> 16:57.390
I can't say
I'm actually surprised,

16:57.434 --> 16:58.641
because, you know,

16:58.685 --> 17:00.518
there were some
definitely glaring

17:00.562 --> 17:01.978
lapses of attention

17:02.022 --> 17:04.939
that basically got
the result that I got.

17:04.983 --> 17:08.693
♪ ♪

17:08.737 --> 17:10.236
You guys are through
to the next round.

17:10.280 --> 17:13.656
Your second challenge
is to turn that blade

17:13.700 --> 17:16.325
into a fully operational weapon.

17:16.369 --> 17:19.579
You must design
and fabricate a handle

17:19.622 --> 17:22.999
from the range of materials
provided for you.

17:23.043 --> 17:26.919
Also, you can address
any flaws in your blade

17:26.963 --> 17:28.588
from round one.

17:28.631 --> 17:31.507
You will have just three hours
to complete this task.

17:31.551 --> 17:34.844
After this round,
your weapons will be tested

17:34.888 --> 17:38.723
on their strength and durability
against a panel of steel,

17:38.767 --> 17:41.809
as well as their ability
to hold an edge

17:41.853 --> 17:44.687
in a specially designed
sharpness test.

17:44.731 --> 17:48.191
At the end of this round,
one of you will be asked

17:48.234 --> 17:51.027
to surrender his weapon
and leave the forge.

17:51.071 --> 17:53.321
Your time starts...

17:53.364 --> 17:54.322
now.

17:54.365 --> 17:56.199
♪ ♪

17:56.242 --> 17:57.241
(J)
Here we go.

17:57.285 --> 18:00.036
♪ ♪

18:00.080 --> 18:02.622
The blade's too long,
and that is a problem,

18:02.665 --> 18:04.624
so I'm gonna grind off
what I don't need.

18:04.667 --> 18:06.042
♪ ♪

18:06.086 --> 18:08.419
I'm hyper focused
on challenge two.

18:08.463 --> 18:10.463
I'm gonna get this right.

18:10.507 --> 18:13.424
I want to finish up the grind
as quickly as possible,

18:13.468 --> 18:15.593
so I can move on
to putting the handle on,

18:15.637 --> 18:18.346
'cause that's gonna take up
a lot of time as well.

18:18.389 --> 18:23.559
♪ ♪

18:23.603 --> 18:25.228
I'm doing a cord-wrapped handle

18:25.271 --> 18:27.063
'cause I think it'll work well
with the knife.

18:27.107 --> 18:28.314
(J)
I got a feeling
that Guy is planning

18:28.358 --> 18:30.441
on wrapping his tang
with the leather

18:30.485 --> 18:33.444
and then putting
the paracord over top.

18:33.488 --> 18:35.238
(Wil)
If you get that looseness
as you're wrapping,

18:35.281 --> 18:37.281
that can really cause a bind
when you get down

18:37.325 --> 18:38.991
to the end of the cord.

18:39.035 --> 18:40.868
(J)
Do you really think
doing a cord-wrapped handle

18:40.912 --> 18:44.622
when $10,000 is on the line
is the way to go?

18:44.666 --> 18:46.916
Absolutely not.

18:46.960 --> 18:51.045
This challenge is one of
the most stressful parts for me.

18:51.089 --> 18:52.922
There are several
warps in my blade

18:52.966 --> 18:54.465
that I need to try
and straighten out

18:54.509 --> 18:56.425
as much as I possibly can.

18:56.469 --> 18:58.928
It seems like this is

18:58.972 --> 19:01.305
a fairly large risk
that Cowboy is taking.

19:01.349 --> 19:04.142
He's putting a lot of torque
on the tip of that blade.

19:04.185 --> 19:06.853
(Cowboy)
When you're working a blade
in a vise like that,

19:06.896 --> 19:09.105
heating it and bending it
like that,

19:09.149 --> 19:10.398
you really risk the chance--

19:10.441 --> 19:11.983
if it hasn't been
tempered right--

19:12.026 --> 19:14.402
that it's gonna snap
and break off right there.

19:14.445 --> 19:16.654
Let's just hope he didn't
overheat his blade

19:16.698 --> 19:17.947
and lose his hardness.

19:17.991 --> 19:19.323
That's the concern.

19:19.367 --> 19:21.784
Right now, the worst thing
I can figure

19:21.828 --> 19:23.536
would be my blade breaking.

19:23.580 --> 19:26.998
(Wil)
He could be getting
into dangerous waters.

19:27.041 --> 19:29.041
Isn't dangerous waters
right now?

19:29.085 --> 19:32.628
♪ ♪

19:36.467 --> 19:40.178
♪ ♪

19:40.221 --> 19:42.305
(Cowboy)
Right now, the worst
thing I can figure

19:42.348 --> 19:43.723
would be my blade breaking

19:43.766 --> 19:47.852
and having to hand in
half of the blade.

19:47.896 --> 19:50.646
♪ ♪

19:50.690 --> 19:52.815
I'm relieved
the blade didn't break.

19:52.859 --> 19:54.984
Now I'm really ready
to start on this handle

19:55.028 --> 19:56.360
and get it accomplished.

19:56.404 --> 19:57.653
♪ ♪

19:57.697 --> 19:58.821
With the handle,
I'm gonna go with

19:58.865 --> 20:00.656
a red and black
synthetic material

20:00.700 --> 20:02.325
because it is a beautiful color.

20:02.368 --> 20:05.411
It symbolizes the fire
and the forging.

20:05.455 --> 20:07.997
The pattern that runs
through this piece

20:08.041 --> 20:10.416
looks similar to the Damascus.

20:10.460 --> 20:11.834
I'm most of the way done.

20:11.878 --> 20:13.377
This is all aesthetics
at this stage now.

20:13.421 --> 20:15.254
(Wil)
One hour, gentlemen.

20:15.298 --> 20:17.632
You have one hour remaining.

20:17.675 --> 20:20.509
♪ ♪

20:20.553 --> 20:23.179
Just putting a handle on a knife
in my own shop

20:23.223 --> 20:25.181
usually takes about
three or four hours,

20:25.225 --> 20:27.516
just the handle.

20:27.560 --> 20:29.018
Peter just cut
the slabs of Micarta.

20:29.062 --> 20:31.020
(Peter)
The specific material I picked

20:31.064 --> 20:33.022
does a real good job
when you contour it.

20:33.066 --> 20:34.774
I do that on every one
of my knives.

20:34.817 --> 20:37.568
It shows the rings
and the layers of the material,

20:37.612 --> 20:41.364
which is actually very pretty.

20:41.407 --> 20:42.698
♪ ♪

20:42.742 --> 20:47.036
I notice Pete swinging
his knife like this.

20:47.080 --> 20:49.747
There is really no finger
protection there at all.

20:49.791 --> 20:52.208
He could have cut
further into the handle,

20:52.252 --> 20:55.419
give it a little more grip
for the index finger and thumb,

20:55.463 --> 20:57.672
so there's less
likelihood of slipping.

20:57.715 --> 20:59.632
It feels good.

20:59.676 --> 21:01.801
Just got to see
how sharp I can get it.

21:01.844 --> 21:02.885
♪ ♪

21:02.929 --> 21:04.887
(Wil)
Ten, nine,

21:04.931 --> 21:06.722
eight, seven,

21:06.766 --> 21:08.724
six, five,

21:08.768 --> 21:10.726
four, three,

21:10.770 --> 21:12.853
two, one.

21:12.897 --> 21:14.146
Your time is up.

21:16.359 --> 21:19.235
This has been definitely
the biggest challenge

21:19.279 --> 21:24.240
I've had in my career,
but I think I own this.

21:24.284 --> 21:25.741
♪ ♪

21:25.785 --> 21:27.827
(Wil)
Bladesmiths,
you have all created

21:27.870 --> 21:30.871
some amazing
and beautiful blades.

21:30.915 --> 21:33.916
Now it's time to see if
they're as tough as they look.

21:33.960 --> 21:35.918
In a moment,
Doug is gonna see

21:35.962 --> 21:39.255
if your blades hold an edge
in our sharpness test.

21:39.299 --> 21:42.133
But first, J is gonna test

21:42.176 --> 21:44.135
your weapon strength
and durability

21:44.178 --> 21:46.762
against these car doors.

21:46.806 --> 21:48.431
J.

21:48.474 --> 21:49.849
(J)
All right, bladesmiths.

21:49.892 --> 21:51.434
I'm gonna attempt
to thrust through

21:51.477 --> 21:54.562
and lever out
your blades three times,

21:54.605 --> 21:56.772
and then we'll check to see
how well they hold up.

21:56.816 --> 21:57.815
♪ ♪

21:57.859 --> 21:58.816
Peter, you're up first.

21:58.860 --> 21:59.817
Are you ready?

21:59.861 --> 22:00.818
Absolutely.

22:00.862 --> 22:02.153
Let's do it.

22:02.196 --> 22:05.489
(Peter)
The car doors look intimidating.

22:05.533 --> 22:08.159
I'm just crossing my fingers
for luck at this point.

22:08.202 --> 22:11.203
[driving rock music]

22:11.247 --> 22:19.253
♪ ♪

22:21.549 --> 22:23.674
(Peter)
That took me by surprise.

22:23.718 --> 22:25.468
I absolutely planned on it

22:25.511 --> 22:28.095
to go in farther
into the steel door.

22:28.139 --> 22:29.513
I'm heartbroken.

22:29.557 --> 22:32.141
Well, Peter,
it held up pretty well.

22:32.185 --> 22:34.143
It's a good thing
I was wearing a heavy glove

22:34.187 --> 22:37.480
because my hand slipped up
a couple of times.

22:37.523 --> 22:40.483
It's got a lot of meat on it,
so it didn't penetrate real far,

22:40.526 --> 22:42.151
and we do have
a little bit of a chip

22:42.195 --> 22:44.362
on the edge up front here.

22:44.405 --> 22:45.571
Okay.

22:45.615 --> 22:47.531
Doug.

22:47.575 --> 22:49.408
♪ ♪

22:49.452 --> 22:51.994
(Doug)
What I'm gonna do now
is a sharpness test.

22:52.038 --> 22:53.829
Now we're gonna test your edge,

22:53.873 --> 22:55.164
see if we can cut
the meat over here.

22:55.208 --> 22:57.208
I will deliver
one backhanded blow,

22:57.251 --> 22:59.168
and we'll see
how far it slices.

22:59.212 --> 23:02.213
[suspenseful music]

23:02.256 --> 23:08.344
♪ ♪

23:08.388 --> 23:10.012
It's got a good edge to it.

23:10.056 --> 23:13.057
It made it a little more
than halfway through.

23:13.101 --> 23:16.435
It did pull forward
on my swing.

23:16.479 --> 23:19.772
It definitely likes to pull
away from you on the guard.

23:19.816 --> 23:20.731
(J)
All right, Guy.

23:20.775 --> 23:21.899
Your blade's up next.

23:21.943 --> 23:23.025
- Are you ready?
- I'm ready.

23:23.069 --> 23:24.693
Let's do it.

23:24.737 --> 23:27.363
I'm kind of looking to prove
that a thin knife

23:27.407 --> 23:30.866
is a good choice compared to
everybody's thicker knives.

23:30.910 --> 23:33.828
[driving rock music]

23:33.871 --> 23:41.252
♪ ♪

23:41.295 --> 23:42.711
Damn.

23:42.755 --> 23:44.380
♪ ♪

23:44.424 --> 23:45.756
Well, Guy, I got to say.

23:45.800 --> 23:48.175
For such a narrow profile,
that fat tip was having

23:48.219 --> 23:50.594
a hard time
getting through there.

23:50.638 --> 23:52.388
But the blade held up well.

23:52.432 --> 23:54.056
Good job on that.

23:54.100 --> 23:55.474
Thanks.

23:55.518 --> 23:56.892
Doug.

23:56.936 --> 23:59.854
[suspenseful music]

23:59.897 --> 24:07.903
♪ ♪

24:11.701 --> 24:13.075
Felt very good.

24:13.119 --> 24:15.578
It cut about halfway
through the meat.

24:15.621 --> 24:17.705
- Good job.
- Thank you.

24:17.748 --> 24:20.082
♪ ♪

24:20.126 --> 24:21.417
All right, Cowboy.

24:21.461 --> 24:22.918
Your knife ready
to cowboy up?

24:22.962 --> 24:24.587
Yeah, I'm ready.

24:24.630 --> 24:27.173
It would be a devastating thing
if I lost this blade.

24:27.216 --> 24:29.592
If it broke
in the middle of this test,

24:29.635 --> 24:31.135
that would be just horrible.

24:31.179 --> 24:36.640
♪ ♪

24:40.897 --> 24:42.605
♪ ♪

24:42.648 --> 24:44.773
All right, Cowboy.

24:44.817 --> 24:46.275
(Cowboy)
I'm ready.

24:46.319 --> 24:48.444
Let's do it.

24:48.488 --> 24:51.447
[driving rock music]

24:51.491 --> 24:59.497
♪ ♪

25:00.875 --> 25:02.583
(Cowboy)
I intentionally put

25:02.627 --> 25:04.502
an armor piercing point
on there.

25:04.545 --> 25:06.295
It should have punched
through the door.

25:06.339 --> 25:07.713
Well, it didn't break.

25:07.757 --> 25:09.131
That's a good thing.

25:09.175 --> 25:13.093
Your tip deformed a bit
on the first thrust,

25:13.137 --> 25:15.554
but she held up.

25:15.598 --> 25:16.972
♪ ♪

25:17.016 --> 25:18.807
Doug.

25:18.851 --> 25:20.976
(Doug)
All right,
since we didn't puncture,

25:21.020 --> 25:24.647
the edge here
should cut meat.

25:24.690 --> 25:27.608
[suspenseful music]

25:27.652 --> 25:34.323
♪ ♪

25:34.367 --> 25:37.493
(Doug)
It made it about
a quarter of the way through.

25:37.537 --> 25:40.371
(Cowboy)
I had a couple
flaws in my blade,

25:40.414 --> 25:41.664
so it makes me a little nervous.

25:41.707 --> 25:43.332
I feel I got
about a 50/50 chance

25:43.376 --> 25:45.167
on whether I'm going
to get eliminated or not.

25:45.211 --> 25:46.669
Out of all three blades,

25:46.712 --> 25:49.171
everybody was strong
in one suit or another,

25:49.215 --> 25:52.007
and I am fearful that I am
gonna be going home.

25:52.051 --> 25:54.426
♪ ♪

25:54.470 --> 25:57.429
[dramatic music]

25:57.473 --> 25:59.056
♪ ♪

25:59.100 --> 26:02.351
Gentlemen, the judges have
had to make their most

26:02.395 --> 26:05.187
difficult decision to date.

26:05.231 --> 26:08.691
♪ ♪

26:08.734 --> 26:12.528
Cowboy, you did not
make the cut.

26:12.572 --> 26:15.447
We love the design,
your choice of material.

26:15.491 --> 26:18.367
Your steel pattern came out
beautifully out of the can,

26:18.411 --> 26:20.369
but when you went
to straighten that blade,

26:20.413 --> 26:22.454
you softened it up too much--

26:22.498 --> 26:25.082
just not a hard enough edge.

26:25.126 --> 26:27.876
Cowboy, it was a pleasure
watching you work,

26:27.920 --> 26:29.753
but you must
surrender your blade.

26:29.797 --> 26:31.171
♪ ♪

26:31.215 --> 26:32.423
I gave it my best,
and I go on from here

26:32.466 --> 26:34.008
with new friends,
new knowledge,

26:34.051 --> 26:37.219
and time to get back to my forge
to satisfy my customers.

26:37.263 --> 26:39.471
To me, it's a win-win situation.

26:39.515 --> 26:44.727
♪ ♪

26:44.770 --> 26:45.686
(Wil)
Guy, Peter.

26:45.730 --> 26:47.187
Congratulations.

26:47.231 --> 26:49.982
You guys are in
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> final.

26:50.026 --> 26:52.901
When you showed up here,
we asked you to use our forge,

26:52.945 --> 26:54.570
our tools and machinery

26:54.614 --> 26:57.448
to create a signature weapon
of your own design.

26:57.491 --> 27:00.284
Now, we're gonna send you
back to your home forge

27:00.328 --> 27:04.246
where we're asking you to create
an iconic weapon from history...

27:04.290 --> 27:07.458
♪ ♪

27:07.501 --> 27:09.460
The Elizabethan rapier.

27:09.503 --> 27:12.004
(J)
The rapier originated
in Italy and Spain

27:12.048 --> 27:15.090
and then gained popularity
throughout Western Europe.

27:15.134 --> 27:17.092
(Wil)
Though they varied
in size and shape,

27:17.136 --> 27:19.928
after the 1500s,
the word rapier came to refer

27:19.972 --> 27:24.141
exclusively to the slender
thrusting sword we now know.

27:24.185 --> 27:26.769
Nearly all of the blades
are rigid, narrow,

27:26.812 --> 27:29.772
become thinner toward the point,
and have a complex hilt

27:29.815 --> 27:33.108
to provide protection
for the hand wielding it.

27:33.152 --> 27:34.610
(J)
They were developed as a weapon

27:34.654 --> 27:38.155
for urban self defense
and private dueling.

27:38.199 --> 27:40.616
(Wil)
Their weight was concentrated
in their hilts,

27:40.660 --> 27:43.619
making for a fast,
single-hand stabbing sword

27:43.663 --> 27:45.204
with a long range that could be

27:45.247 --> 27:49.124
used in the street, back alley,
or an enclosed space.

27:49.168 --> 27:51.543
Whether it's wielded
by Inigo Montoya

27:51.587 --> 27:54.463
in<i> The Princess Bride</i>
or the three musketeers,

27:54.507 --> 27:57.758
the rapier is easily one
of the most recognizable blades

27:57.802 --> 28:00.636
in film and literature.

28:00.680 --> 28:05.140
You will have five days
to forge an Elizabethan rapier.

28:05.184 --> 28:09.061
It must be an authentic,
fully functioning version

28:09.105 --> 28:10.813
of that classic weapon.

28:10.856 --> 28:12.523
When the five days are up,

28:12.566 --> 28:14.358
you will bring
your rapiers back here

28:14.402 --> 28:16.235
and present them to our judges.

28:16.278 --> 28:17.653
They will put them through

28:17.697 --> 28:21.407
a series of dynamic
and grueling tests.

28:21.450 --> 28:24.827
When those tests are complete,
the judges will decide

28:24.870 --> 28:28.163
who will walk
with a check for $10,000

28:28.207 --> 28:31.667
and be crowned
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

28:31.711 --> 28:33.001
We'll see you in five days.

28:33.045 --> 28:34.002
Good luck.

28:37.425 --> 28:40.426
[driving rock music]

28:40.469 --> 28:42.177
♪ ♪

28:42.221 --> 28:44.513
(Guy)
I worked for a company
that produced rapiers.

28:44.557 --> 28:47.141
I've made parts for rapiers;
I've assembled the rapiers,

28:47.184 --> 28:50.227
but I've never done all of it
from start to finish.

28:50.271 --> 28:53.063
[metal clanging]

28:53.107 --> 28:55.774
It's very important
to try and keep it straight.

28:55.818 --> 28:57.401
♪ ♪

28:57.445 --> 28:58.610
This thing's a beast,

28:58.654 --> 29:00.696
roughly 48 inches of steel.

29:00.740 --> 29:02.406
That's about 20 inches longer

29:02.450 --> 29:04.575
than I would normally
make a blade.

29:04.618 --> 29:08.078
This is gonna be a nightmare.

29:08.122 --> 29:11.123
[driving rock music]

29:11.167 --> 29:14.376
♪ ♪

29:14.420 --> 29:17.546
(Peter)
They requested me
to make a rapier.

29:17.590 --> 29:19.757
Difficulty factor
on a 1 to 10 scale,

29:19.800 --> 29:21.091
I would give it an 11.

29:21.135 --> 29:22.593
♪ ♪

29:22.636 --> 29:24.887
I don't have the equipment
for this thing.

29:24.930 --> 29:28.015
I'm gonna have to
do something different.

29:28.058 --> 29:29.725
So this is what the guy said

29:29.769 --> 29:32.102
when he said,
"Adapt and overcome," right?

29:32.146 --> 29:33.729
♪ ♪

29:33.773 --> 29:35.731
I'm setting up these two ovens
back-to-back,

29:35.775 --> 29:39.943
but the sword's longer than both
of them things put together.

29:39.987 --> 29:42.738
I had to pile up fire bricks
in between it,

29:42.782 --> 29:44.281
and I covered the center
with Kaowool

29:44.325 --> 29:46.325
to keep thermal
efficiency there.

29:46.368 --> 29:49.411
Hopefully we won't have
too many surprises

29:49.455 --> 29:50.704
when I go to heat treat it.

29:50.748 --> 29:54.249
♪ ♪

29:54.293 --> 29:56.418
(Guy)
I'm getting ready
to do the heat treating.

29:56.462 --> 29:58.253
I'm not sure exactly what
I'm gonna get out of it.

29:58.297 --> 30:00.255
I'm a little concerned about it.

30:00.299 --> 30:01.507
[bleep] get in there.

30:04.303 --> 30:07.095
♪ ♪

30:07.139 --> 30:08.931
The blade actually
heat treated solid,

30:08.974 --> 30:10.307
and it's pretty damn straight.

30:10.351 --> 30:11.934
That's looking really good.

30:11.977 --> 30:13.936
Now I got to start the handle.

30:13.979 --> 30:17.773
♪ ♪

30:17.817 --> 30:20.526
I'm trying to heat the metal up
so I can get it to bend.

30:20.569 --> 30:22.402
I don't have a good heat source
other than the forge,

30:22.446 --> 30:24.488
and it's just not working.

30:24.532 --> 30:25.948
♪ ♪

30:25.991 --> 30:28.116
I really wanted
something dramatic,

30:28.160 --> 30:29.368
but I'm not getting it

30:29.411 --> 30:31.453
to come together
and align properly.

30:31.497 --> 30:35.624
It looks like it's
a junkyard fabrication.

30:35.668 --> 30:38.460
It's time to cut my losses.

30:38.504 --> 30:42.297
Basically it's just
a time sink at this point.

30:42.341 --> 30:44.174
Yeah, I don't think
I can do this.

30:45.427 --> 30:47.469
♪ ♪

30:47.513 --> 30:49.429
(Peter)
First thing this morning,
I'm going to quench the blade

30:49.473 --> 30:53.141
into a cylindrical tube of oil
that's 60 inches long.

30:53.185 --> 30:55.978
Many problems can happen
in the quench.

30:56.021 --> 30:58.313
The biggest thing is that
it cracks.

30:58.357 --> 31:01.024
Cross your fingers
that it doesn't self-destruct.

31:01.068 --> 31:07.030
♪ ♪

31:07.074 --> 31:12.035
Well, I didn't hear it go ping,
so that's really a good thing,

31:12.079 --> 31:13.453
'cause wn they go ping,

31:13.497 --> 31:14.830
you can just pretty much
drop it in the oil tank.

31:14.874 --> 31:16.748
It's over with.

31:16.792 --> 31:18.709
♪ ♪

31:18.752 --> 31:21.128
(Guy)
Today is all about
getting the sword together.

31:21.171 --> 31:23.213
I made an elliptical shaped
guard

31:23.257 --> 31:25.424
so you have a reference
in your grip.

31:25.467 --> 31:26.550
You always know
where the cutting edge is.

31:26.594 --> 31:28.260
This is what it's gonna be.

31:28.304 --> 31:31.889
It's far, far and away
simpler than the previous guard.

31:31.932 --> 31:33.015
♪ ♪

31:33.058 --> 31:34.933
Test the balance.

31:34.977 --> 31:36.226
I'm delighted it's done.

31:36.270 --> 31:38.937
The sword I made is simple,

31:38.981 --> 31:40.939
and the one I wanted
was far more sophisticated,

31:40.983 --> 31:43.775
but I'm satisfied
with the sword.

31:43.819 --> 31:46.945
♪ ♪

31:46.989 --> 31:50.157
(Peter)
I'm going to start
on the basket hilt.

31:50.200 --> 31:53.577
I saw an example that almost
looked like deer horns,

31:53.621 --> 31:55.078
which I thought was really cool.

31:55.122 --> 31:57.623
I want to create something
similar to that.

31:57.666 --> 31:59.917
I'm doing the best I can
with the time allotted.

31:59.960 --> 32:01.293
♪ ♪

32:01.337 --> 32:03.295
I'm absolutely
nervous as a June bride.

32:03.339 --> 32:06.298
The blade has to be
final finished and sharpened.

32:06.342 --> 32:09.051
I still have fluting
to do on the handle.

32:09.094 --> 32:11.970
I'm gonna try to incorporate
this as the butt cap.

32:12.014 --> 32:15.015
There's still plenty to do
and not a lot of time to do it.

32:15.059 --> 32:22.689
♪ ♪

32:28.697 --> 32:30.322
♪ ♪

32:30.366 --> 32:34.701
Guy, Peter,
welcome back to the forge.

32:34.745 --> 32:37.621
Looks like your time at home
was productive.

32:37.665 --> 32:40.707
Guy, tell us a little bit
about your weapon.

32:40.751 --> 32:43.460
(Guy)
We had to make a rapier
of the Elizabethan period.

32:43.504 --> 32:44.878
I opted for a Spanish variant.

32:44.922 --> 32:46.463
The guard is pretty crude.

32:46.507 --> 32:47.547
I just made it
out of mild steel.

32:47.591 --> 32:48.966
It's been forge blackened.

32:49.009 --> 32:50.634
The handle is made out of
a buckeye burl.

32:50.678 --> 32:52.427
Pretty simple construction,
actually.

32:52.471 --> 32:53.470
(Wil)
Okay.

32:53.514 --> 32:55.347
Peter, how'd it go for you?

32:55.391 --> 32:56.848
(Peter)
Not having ever made one,

32:56.892 --> 32:59.601
a lot of seat-of-the-pants
manufacturing there.

32:59.645 --> 33:01.520
I'm very confident
about the blade itself.

33:01.563 --> 33:04.189
At least I know that the
heat treat was done properly.

33:04.233 --> 33:06.650
When it came to making
the basket hilt,

33:06.694 --> 33:09.152
it's not an exact copy
of any one thing.

33:09.196 --> 33:11.154
I just put pieces where
I thought they would need to be

33:11.198 --> 33:14.074
in order to protect your hand
during a combat situation.

33:14.118 --> 33:15.033
(Wil)
Great.

33:15.077 --> 33:16.827
All right, gentlemen.

33:16.870 --> 33:20.747
Both of your blades will now
be put through three trials.

33:20.791 --> 33:24.126
There will be a slice test;
there will be a kill test;

33:24.169 --> 33:26.461
and there will be
a strength test.

33:26.505 --> 33:29.756
First up is the slice test.

33:29.800 --> 33:31.758
Doug.

33:31.802 --> 33:33.844
♪ ♪

33:33.887 --> 33:36.263
Gentlemen, to test
the sharpness of your tip,

33:36.306 --> 33:39.016
I will run it across
this ballistic bag

33:39.059 --> 33:40.100
and then thrust it in

33:40.144 --> 33:41.685
to see how sharp your tip is.

33:41.729 --> 33:42.728
Guy, you're up first.

33:42.771 --> 33:44.354
- Are you ready?
- Ready.

33:44.398 --> 33:45.355
Let's do this.

33:45.399 --> 33:48.316
[suspenseful music]

33:48.360 --> 33:56.366
♪ ♪

34:04.084 --> 34:07.711
It does have a good
slicing ability

34:07.755 --> 34:09.546
and thrust capability.

34:09.590 --> 34:11.465
With this particular grip,

34:11.508 --> 34:13.300
it makes it more difficult
to control the weapon

34:13.343 --> 34:18.555
because of the length,
but it'll slice.

34:18.599 --> 34:19.973
All right, Peter.

34:20.017 --> 34:20.932
You're up next.

34:20.976 --> 34:22.017
Are you ready?

34:22.061 --> 34:23.727
As ready as I'll ever be.

34:23.771 --> 34:25.395
Let's do this.

34:25.439 --> 34:28.398
[suspenseful music]

34:28.442 --> 34:36.448
♪ ♪

34:45.417 --> 34:46.541
[sighs]

34:46.585 --> 34:49.586
♪ ♪

34:49.630 --> 34:52.964
Well, Peter.

34:53.008 --> 34:54.591
It's very heavy.

34:54.635 --> 34:58.762
I could not grip it properly
to get a good recovery.

34:58.806 --> 34:59.846
It is sharp.

34:59.890 --> 35:01.431
It will thrust,

35:01.475 --> 35:05.143
but I can not properly deliver
multiple strikes with it.

35:05.187 --> 35:08.271
Next up is the kill test.

35:08.315 --> 35:10.398
For this, I will
hand you over to Dave,

35:10.442 --> 35:12.901
who is an expert
on European weapons.

35:12.945 --> 35:15.028
♪ ♪

35:15.072 --> 35:17.948
Gentlemen, in my opinion,
the Elizabethan rapier

35:17.991 --> 35:20.450
is one of the most
elegant weapons ever created.

35:20.494 --> 35:22.994
This is not
a battlefield weapon.

35:23.038 --> 35:25.455
This weapon was designed
for civilian use,

35:25.499 --> 35:29.292
and everything about it
was dialed in for the duel.

35:29.336 --> 35:30.961
To test your weapons,

35:31.004 --> 35:33.213
we've got these
ballistic gel dummies.

35:33.257 --> 35:34.881
We put them in a doublet
to simulate

35:34.925 --> 35:37.801
the clothing of the period.

35:37.845 --> 35:38.969
Guy, you're up first.

35:39.012 --> 35:39.970
Are you ready?

35:40.013 --> 35:41.513
- Yep.
- All right.

35:41.557 --> 35:43.140
I feel quite confident

35:43.183 --> 35:46.059
the rapier is gonna do
an outstanding job on the dummy.

35:46.103 --> 35:48.645
I don't really foresee
any problems with it whatsoever.

35:48.689 --> 35:51.690
[driving rock music]

35:51.733 --> 35:59.739
♪ ♪

36:09.543 --> 36:11.835
(Dave)
Let's see what damage we did.

36:11.879 --> 36:17.674
The shot to the belly went in
about 8 to 10 inches.

36:17.718 --> 36:19.009
Kind of went
a little high there,

36:19.052 --> 36:21.052
took him right in the chin.

36:21.096 --> 36:22.345
That would have gone
right into his mouth,

36:22.389 --> 36:23.805
right into the brain.

36:23.849 --> 36:26.558
♪ ♪

36:26.602 --> 36:30.187
So all in all,
to quote a friend of mine,

36:30.230 --> 36:31.354
it will kill.

36:31.398 --> 36:34.274
[laughs]

36:34.318 --> 36:37.527
- So, Peter, you ready?
- Sure.

36:37.571 --> 36:40.238
This is a true test
of the sword's ability,

36:40.282 --> 36:41.781
and if it's gonna fail,

36:41.825 --> 36:42.866
this is where
it's going to fail.

36:42.910 --> 36:45.911
[driving rock music]

36:45.954 --> 36:53.960
♪ ♪

37:00.552 --> 37:03.720
(Dave)
Let's open it up,
see how we did.

37:03.764 --> 37:05.055
All right, well,
you can see

37:05.098 --> 37:09.517
that shot to the belly
just went right in.

37:09.561 --> 37:13.063
I actually think I hit
the spine on that one.

37:13.106 --> 37:16.233
There's an exit wound
back here.

37:16.276 --> 37:18.235
It was sticking right through.

37:18.278 --> 37:20.237
It'll definitely kill.

37:20.280 --> 37:21.905
He stabbed the thing
through the neck,

37:21.949 --> 37:24.282
and the blade was
out the back a foot,

37:24.326 --> 37:26.201
so it was like, yay.

37:26.245 --> 37:27.577
[laughs]

37:27.621 --> 37:30.288
So I was very happy
at that point.

37:30.332 --> 37:33.291
Gentlemen, next is
the strength test.

37:33.335 --> 37:35.627
Now, what made
the rapier possible

37:35.671 --> 37:37.587
were advances in metallurgy,

37:37.631 --> 37:40.840
making for a longer,
thinner, stronger blade

37:40.884 --> 37:43.301
that had a good stiff spine

37:43.345 --> 37:45.929
but enough flexibility
that it wouldn't break.

37:45.973 --> 37:48.306
What we're gonna do is,
we're gonna place your blade

37:48.350 --> 37:50.392
tip down
in this rack

37:50.435 --> 37:53.937
and flex it to 35 degrees
in one direction,

37:53.981 --> 37:56.147
35 degrees
in the other direction,

37:56.191 --> 37:58.400
make sure that temper's right
and that that blade

37:58.443 --> 38:00.777
doesn't pick up a set
in either way.

38:00.821 --> 38:01.778
Holy crap.

38:01.822 --> 38:03.280
This is gonna be a nightmare.

38:10.664 --> 38:12.789
(Dave)
Next is the strength test.

38:12.833 --> 38:14.624
Guy, you ready?

38:14.668 --> 38:15.959
- Oh, yeah.
- All right.

38:16.003 --> 38:18.461
Normally, I would be
a bit offended

38:18.505 --> 38:23.133
at somebody leveraging
a blade I make into some block

38:23.176 --> 38:24.968
and seeing how far
they could bend it.

38:25.012 --> 38:26.928
I can forgive in this situation.

38:26.972 --> 38:32.309
♪ ♪

38:32.352 --> 38:33.310
There are 10...

38:33.353 --> 38:35.520
♪ ♪

38:35.564 --> 38:36.521
20...

38:36.565 --> 38:41.026
♪ ♪

38:41.069 --> 38:42.193
30...

38:42.237 --> 38:43.737
Going all the way to 35.

38:43.780 --> 38:48.658
♪ ♪

38:48.702 --> 38:52.162
It's right at the peg.

38:52.205 --> 38:53.705
All right, going
the other direction.

38:53.749 --> 38:56.291
♪ ♪

38:56.335 --> 38:57.292
10...

38:57.336 --> 39:00.503
♪ ♪

39:00.547 --> 39:02.630
20...

39:02.674 --> 39:05.258
♪ ♪

39:05.302 --> 39:07.510
There's 30...

39:07.554 --> 39:08.887
All the way.

39:08.930 --> 39:11.348
♪ ♪

39:11.391 --> 39:12.974
There's 35.

39:13.018 --> 39:17.687
♪ ♪

39:17.731 --> 39:19.898
Didn't pick up a set.

39:19.941 --> 39:21.483
Didn't break.

39:21.526 --> 39:23.360
Nicely tempered.

39:23.403 --> 39:24.861
Thank you.

39:24.905 --> 39:26.571
(Dave)
So, Peter, you ready?

39:26.615 --> 39:27.655
Ready as I'll ever be.

39:27.699 --> 39:29.366
Okay.

39:29.409 --> 39:32.035
I'm standing there like this
crossing my fingers.

39:32.079 --> 39:34.954
Anybody in the knife business
knows that bending it

39:34.998 --> 39:38.625
back and forth multiple times
will create a failure.

39:38.668 --> 39:43.546
♪ ♪

39:43.590 --> 39:44.714
10...

39:44.758 --> 39:47.717
♪ ♪

39:47.761 --> 39:49.344
20...

39:49.388 --> 39:52.722
♪ ♪

39:52.766 --> 39:54.015
That's 30...

39:54.059 --> 39:55.642
♪ ♪

39:55.685 --> 39:59.270
Going to the peg...

39:59.314 --> 40:00.605
35.

40:00.649 --> 40:03.066
♪ ♪

40:03.110 --> 40:04.818
Here we go
in the other direction.

40:04.861 --> 40:07.654
♪ ♪

40:07.697 --> 40:08.696
10...

40:08.740 --> 40:11.032
♪ ♪

40:11.076 --> 40:12.867
20...

40:12.911 --> 40:15.662
♪ ♪

40:15.705 --> 40:16.663
30...

40:16.706 --> 40:18.706
♪ ♪

40:18.750 --> 40:20.333
Going to 35...

40:20.377 --> 40:23.878
♪ ♪

40:23.922 --> 40:24.879
Right to the peg.

40:24.923 --> 40:27.757
♪ ♪

40:27.801 --> 40:29.634
Well, the blade stayed true.

40:29.678 --> 40:30.677
Thank God.

40:30.720 --> 40:31.636
Nicely tempered.

40:31.680 --> 40:32.679
Thank God.

40:32.722 --> 40:33.638
Sigh of relief, huh?

40:33.682 --> 40:35.390
Absolutely.

40:35.434 --> 40:37.600
I'm very nervous,
very anxious.

40:37.644 --> 40:39.269
I feel that
there's a good possibility

40:39.312 --> 40:41.980
I may be eliminated
in this final challenge

40:42.023 --> 40:43.440
due to the weight factor.

40:43.483 --> 40:45.817
I'm apprehensive
about the entire thing.

40:47.904 --> 40:50.447
♪ ♪

40:50.490 --> 40:53.074
Gentlemen, through three
rounds of competition,

40:53.118 --> 40:55.118
you've both worked
incredibly hard

40:55.162 --> 40:57.036
to produce some
outstanding work,

40:57.080 --> 40:59.164
but in this competition,
there can only be

40:59.207 --> 41:02.459
one winner of $10,000.

41:02.502 --> 41:05.587
Guy, I really like the bladework
you did on that.

41:05.630 --> 41:07.464
It's got a very nice
taper at the point.

41:07.507 --> 41:08.631
I would have liked
to see more taper

41:08.675 --> 41:10.175
all the way down the blade.

41:10.218 --> 41:12.510
I mean, I would like to see it
squared off more,

41:12.554 --> 41:15.555
but very nicely done.

41:15.599 --> 41:17.640
It is tip heavy,

41:17.684 --> 41:20.018
but it still
performed quite well.

41:20.061 --> 41:21.352
I like the design of the handle.

41:21.396 --> 41:23.354
I was able to get
a good grip on it.

41:23.398 --> 41:25.148
♪ ♪

41:25.192 --> 41:29.152
Pete, also beautiful
bladework on that.

41:29.196 --> 41:31.863
For your first time
with such long, thin blades,

41:31.907 --> 41:33.448
I got to commend you.

41:33.492 --> 41:36.993
And the craftsmanship
on that handle is beautiful.

41:37.037 --> 41:41.039
The only real problem I had
was on your guard,

41:41.082 --> 41:42.999
being able to loop
my finger over there.

41:43.043 --> 41:45.126
It's so wide at that point,

41:45.170 --> 41:49.589
that it was just
uncomfortable in that task.

41:49.633 --> 41:51.174
♪ ♪

41:51.218 --> 41:53.343
(Wil)
You've both done
exceptional work.

41:53.386 --> 41:54.928
This decision was not easy.

41:54.971 --> 41:59.057
♪ ♪

41:59.100 --> 42:00.308
Guy...

42:02.687 --> 42:04.062
You are
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

42:04.105 --> 42:05.480
Congratulations.

42:05.524 --> 42:06.689
[bleep].

42:06.733 --> 42:07.774
♪ ♪

42:07.817 --> 42:09.025
[laughs]

42:09.069 --> 42:11.694
Pete, you did not make the cut.

42:11.738 --> 42:14.531
Well, Pete, overall
you made a beautiful piece,

42:14.574 --> 42:17.033
but the big issue was

42:17.077 --> 42:18.826
overbalance in the front
of the blade,

42:18.870 --> 42:20.537
making it very tip-heavy.

42:20.580 --> 42:22.872
Because of the stretch
in the handle

42:22.916 --> 42:24.207
and that heavy weight there,

42:24.251 --> 42:25.208
those were the reasons

42:25.252 --> 42:26.376
we had to cut you loose.

42:26.419 --> 42:27.627
Understood.

42:27.671 --> 42:30.171
Pete, please surrender
your weapon.

42:30.215 --> 42:34.842
♪ ♪

42:34.886 --> 42:37.595
I'm still very proud of myself
for coming this far.

42:37.639 --> 42:39.722
To win with this would be great,

42:39.766 --> 42:41.808
but to lose,
I have to lose with pride.

42:41.851 --> 42:42.183
♪ ♪

42:42.894 --> 42:44.310
Guy, congratulations.

42:44.354 --> 42:45.937
You are the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion,

42:45.981 --> 42:48.898
and you'll be receiving
a check for $10,000.

42:48.942 --> 42:49.983
How do you feel?

42:50.026 --> 42:51.192
Pretty damn good.

42:51.236 --> 42:52.610
[laughs]

42:52.654 --> 42:54.445
You did a beautiful job
on that blade.

42:54.489 --> 42:56.614
A big thing for me
is functionality.

42:56.658 --> 42:57.615
Your fit-up was solid.

42:57.659 --> 42:58.950
Your sword was solid.

42:58.994 --> 43:00.952
You just performed better
in the tasks.

43:00.996 --> 43:01.995
(Guy)
I'm totally stunned.

43:02.038 --> 43:03.037
It's great.

43:03.081 --> 43:04.038
It's really cool.

43:04.082 --> 43:09.669
♪ ♪
